Project: Identify Customer Segments¶

In this project, you will apply unsupervised learning techniques to identify segments of the population that form the core customer base for a mail-order sales company in Germany. These segments can then be used to direct marketing campaigns towards audiences that will have the highest expected rate of returns. The data that you will use has been provided by our partners at Bertelsmann Arvato Analytics, and represents a real-life data science task.

This notebook will help you complete this task by providing a framework within which you will perform your analysis steps. Feel free to add additional code and markdown cells as you go along so that you can explore everything in precise chunks. The code cells provided in the base template will outline only the major tasks, and will usually not be enough to cover all of the minor tasks that comprise it.

Step 0: Load the Data¶

There are four files associated with this project (not including this one):

  • Udacity_AZDIAS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for the general population of Germany; 891211 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Udacity_CUSTOMERS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for customers of a mail-order company; 191652 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Data_Dictionary.md: Detailed information file about the features in the provided datasets.
  • AZDIAS_Feature_Summary.csv: Summary of feature attributes for demographics data; 85 features (rows) x 4 columns

Each row of the demographics files represents a single person, but also includes information outside of individuals, including information about their household, building, and neighborhood. You will use this information to cluster the general population into groups with similar demographic properties. Then, you will see how the people in the customers dataset fit into those created clusters. The hope here is that certain clusters are over-represented in the customers data, as compared to the general population; those over-represented clusters will be assumed to be part of the core userbase. This information can then be used for further applications, such as targeting for a marketing campaign.

To start off with, load in the demographics data for the general population into a pandas DataFrame, and do the same for the feature attributes summary. Note for all of the .csv data files in this project: they're semicolon (;) delimited, so you'll need an additional argument in your read_csv() call to read in the data properly. Also, considering the size of the main dataset, it may take some time for it to load completely.

Once the dataset is loaded, it's recommended that you take a little bit of time just browsing the general structure of the dataset and feature summary file. You'll be getting deep into the innards of the cleaning in the first major step of the project, so gaining some general familiarity can help you get your bearings.

Step 1.1.1: Convert Missing Value Codes to NaNs¶

The fourth column of the feature attributes summary (loaded in above as feat_info) documents the codes from the data dictionary that indicate missing or unknown data. While the file encodes this as a list (e.g. [-1,0]), this will get read in as a string object. You'll need to do a little bit of parsing to make use of it to identify and clean the data. Convert data that matches a 'missing' or 'unknown' value code into a numpy NaN value. You might want to see how much data takes on a 'missing' or 'unknown' code, and how much data is naturally missing, as a point of interest.

As one more reminder, you are encouraged to add additional cells to break up your analysis into manageable chunks.

# Checking all possibilities
print("All possible missing values: ")
print(feat_info.missing_or_unknown.unique())

# Nans before
CountNulls = azdias.isna().sum().sum()

# Replacing the missing values with nan
for Column in feat_info.iterrows(): 
    # Transforming the string to a list and cast integers to number.
    MissingValues = [val if re.match('^[-]?[0-9]+$', val) is None else int(val) 
                     for val in Column[1].missing_or_unknown.strip('[]').split(',')]

    # Replacing ints in the string with int
    azdias[Column[1].attribute] = azdias[Column[1].attribute].replace(MissingValues, np.nan)
    
# Message
print('\n\nNumber of Nans moved from ' + str(f'{CountNulls:,}') + ' to ' + 
      str(str(f'{azdias.isna().sum().sum():,}')))

Discussion 1.1.2: Assess Missing Data in Each Column¶

Columns Missing Data¶

Using a boxplot, 6 outlier columns were identified as having a large number of missing values. The threshold was set to 200k missing values based on that and the 6 columns were dropped. These columns are: AGER_TYP, GEBURTSJAHR, TITEL_KZ, ALTER_HH, KK_KUNDENTYP, KBA05_BAUMAX. 3 of these columns are on a person level, 2 on a household level, and the last one on microcell_rr3.

One thing to point out is that the only interval column in the dataset was dropped in this step.

Rows Missing Data¶

By transforming the dataframe to 0 for non missing values and 1 for missing values, we can calculate if there is any correlation between the missing values in different variables. What we're trying to check is that, if there are missing values in a column, are we going to find missing values in some other ones.

Based on the heatmap, I found that, indeed, the missing values are correlated in the data. This means that we're missing values for certain individuals in particular and when we miss a few values for a person, we are likely not to have enough information about that person in general.

Step 1.1.3: Assess Missing Data in Each Row¶

Now, you'll perform a similar assessment for the rows of the dataset. How much data is missing in each row? As with the columns, you should see some groups of points that have a very different numbers of missing values. Divide the data into two subsets: one for data points that are above some threshold for missing values, and a second subset for points below that threshold.

In order to know what to do with the outlier rows, we should see if the distribution of data values on columns that are not missing data (or are missing very little data) are similar or different between the two groups. Select at least five of these columns and compare the distribution of values.

  • You can use seaborn's countplot() function to create a bar chart of code frequencies and matplotlib's subplot() function to put bar charts for the two subplots side by side.
  • To reduce repeated code, you might want to write a function that can perform this comparison, taking as one of its arguments a column to be compared.

Depending on what you observe in your comparison, this will have implications on how you approach your conclusions later in the analysis. If the distributions of non-missing features look similar between the data with many missing values and the data with few or no missing values, then we could argue that simply dropping those points from the analysis won't present a major issue. On the other hand, if the data with many missing values looks very different from the data with few or no missing values, then we should make a note on those data as special. We'll revisit these data later on. Either way, you should continue your analysis for now using just the subset of the data with few or no missing values.

# Function to compare
def CompareColumns(SubSet1, SubSet2, ColumnName, SubSet1Name, SubSet2Name):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 3), dpi=80, facecolor='w', edgecolor='k')
    plt.suptitle('Comparison ' + ColumnName)
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.title(SubSet1Name)
    sns.countplot(SubSet1[ColumnName], palette = 'colorblind')
    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.title(SubSet2Name)
    sns.countplot(SubSet2[ColumnName], palette = 'colorblind')

# Additional functions to organise everything. This will be important when transforming the customers dataset
# to match the same structure of the demographics one.
def GetOutliersColumns(df, feat_dict, limit = 200000):
    '''
    Because the customers data might have a different number of outliers, creating a function that returns the list of outliers
    from the original dataset to make sure we drop the same columns in both datasets.
    INPUT: Demographics dataframe.
    OUTPUT: List of outlier columns based on limit of 200k (adjustable)
    '''
    df = ReplaceMissingValues(df, feat_dict)
    CountMissingVals = df.isna().sum()
    return list(CountMissingVals[CountMissingVals > limit].index)


def ReplaceMissingValues(df, feat_dict):
    '''
    Function to replace the missing values in the dataset with nan
    INPUT: Demographics or customers dataframe.
    OUTPUT: Dataset with Nan values.
    '''
    # Replacing the missing values with nan
    for Column in feat_dict.iterrows(): 
        # Transforming the string to a list and cast integers to number.
        MissingValues = [val if re.match('^[-]?[0-9]+$', val) is None else int(val) for val in Column[1].missing_or_unknown.strip('[]').split(',')]

        # Replacing ints in the string with int
        df[Column[1].attribute] = df[Column[1].attribute].replace(MissingValues, np.nan)
    return df

def clean_data(df, outliersList, feat_info, outlierrowmax = 7):
    """a
    Perform feature trimming, re-encoding, and engineering for demographics
    data. 
    
    I modified this function to have better control over the outlier columns that are dropped from the data.
    
    INPUT: Demographics DataFrame, list of outliers to drop, dictionary of data.
    OUTPUT: Trimmed and cleaned demographics DataFrame
    """
    
    # Transform to nans
    df = ReplaceMissingValues(df, feat_info)
    
    # Remove outliers
    df = df.drop(outliersList, axis = 1)
    
    # Remove missing values rows
    MissingValuesRows = df.isna().sum(axis = 1)
    df = df[df.index.isin(MissingValuesRows[MissingValuesRows<=outlierrowmax].index)]
    
    # select, re-encode, and engineer column values.
    CategoricalVariables = feat_info[feat_info.type == 'categorical'].attribute.values
    CategoricalVariables = list(set(CategoricalVariables) - (set(CategoricalVariables) - set(df.columns)))

    # find binary and multi level
    CountUnique = df[CategoricalVariables].nunique()
    BinaryVariables = list(CountUnique[CountUnique == 2].index)
    MultiVariables = list(CountUnique[CountUnique > 2].index)

    # Binary to be reencoded
    BinaryReencode = []
    for Binary in BinaryVariables:
        UniqueValues = list(df[Binary].unique())
        if all(isinstance(item, str) for item in UniqueValues):
            BinaryReencode.append(Binary)

    # Dropping the multi variable columns for now until I test the clustering. Might transform to dummies if needed. 
    df = df.drop(MultiVariables, axis = 1)
    
    # Remapping values
    for Binary in BinaryReencode:
        UniqueValues = df[Binary].unique()
        MappingDict = {oldval:newval for newval, oldval in enumerate(UniqueValues)}
        df[Binary] = df[Binary].map(MappingDict)
        
    # Creating mapping dictionaries
    GenerationMapping = {1: 40, 2: 40, 3: 50, 4: 50, 5: 60, 6: 60, 7: 60, 8: 70, 9: 70,
        10: 80, 11: 80, 12: 80, 13: 80, 14: 90, 15: 90}

    MovementMapping = {1: 0, 2: 1, 3: 0, 4: 1, 5: 0, 6: 1, 7: 1, 8: 0, 9: 1, 10: 0, 11: 1, 12: 0, 13: 1, 14: 0, 15: 1}

    # Create 2 new columns
    df['GENERATION'] = df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE']
    df['MOVEMENT'] = df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE']

    # Mapping new columns
    df['GENERATION'] = df['GENERATION'].map(GenerationMapping)
    df['MOVEMENT'] = df['MOVEMENT'].map(MovementMapping)
        
    # Creating new columns
    df['WEALTH'] = df['CAMEO_INTL_2015']
    df['LIFE_STAGE'] = df['CAMEO_INTL_2015']

    # Apply transformation
    df['WEALTH'] = df['WEALTH'].astype(float) // 10
    df['LIFE_STAGE'] = df['LIFE_STAGE'].astype(float) % 10
    
    # Dropping original columns
    df = df.drop(['CAMEO_INTL_2015', 'PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'], axis =1 )

                        
    # Filtering mixed columns in the data
    MixedColumns = feat_info[feat_info['attribute'].isin(df.columns)][feat_info.type == 'mixed'].attribute.values

    # Drop columns
    df = df.drop(MixedColumns, axis = 1)

    # Cast everything to float
    df = df.astype(float)

    # Return the cleaned dataframe.
    
    return df

Discussion 2.1: Apply Feature Scaling¶

Out of all the variables that we have (66), only 6 are numeric variables. Because of this, I chose the most_frequent methodology to populate the nan values in the dataset. By doing this, I make sure that I don't create any new values that do not exist for the categorical variables. For example, if the methodology was the mean, binary missing values will be replaced by values between 0 and 1 which is not possible in this case.

Another methodology would be splitting the categorical and ordinal from the numeric data and apply two types of imputations on each category. The most_frequent on the categorical and ordinal and the mean or median on the numeric data.

By looking at the initial description of the dataset, we can clearly see that there are some variables that are larger than others. For instance, the mean of GEBURTSJAHR is 1101 while the mean of FINANZTYP is 3.79. This will have an impact on the clustering as larger values will lead to higher distances between points.

Because of that, the data is scaled to have a mean of 0 and std of 1 so that all the variables have the same impact on the clustering step.

Step 2.3: Interpret Principal Components¶

Now that we have our transformed principal components, it's a nice idea to check out the weight of each variable on the first few components to see if they can be interpreted in some fashion.

As a reminder, each principal component is a unit vector that points in the direction of highest variance (after accounting for the variance captured by earlier principal components). The further a weight is from zero, the more the principal component is in the direction of the corresponding feature. If two features have large weights of the same sign (both positive or both negative), then increases in one tend expect to be associated with increases in the other. To contrast, features with different signs can be expected to show a negative correlation: increases in one variable should result in a decrease in the other.

  • To investigate the features, you should map each weight to their corresponding feature name, then sort the features according to weight. The most interesting features for each principal component, then, will be those at the beginning and end of the sorted list. Use the data dictionary document to help you understand these most prominent features, their relationships, and what a positive or negative value on the principal component might indicate.
  • You should investigate and interpret feature associations from the first three principal components in this substep. To help facilitate this, you should write a function that you can call at any time to print the sorted list of feature weights, for the i-th principal component. This might come in handy in the next step of the project, when you interpret the tendencies of the discovered clusters.
In [54]:
def ExplainPCA(ColumnNames, PCAObj, Index, topk = 5, Visualize = True, PrintAll = False):
    Weights = pd.DataFrame()
    Weights['features'] = list(ColumnNames)
    Weights['weights'] = list(PCAObj.components_[Index])
    Weights.sort_values(by = 'weights', inplace = True, ascending = False)
    TopK = Weights[:5]
    
    if Visualize:
        plt.figure(num=None, figsize=(14, 4), dpi=80, facecolor='w', edgecolor='k')
        plt.title('Top Features')
        plt.bar(TopK['features'], TopK['weights'])
        plt.show()
        
    if PrintAll:
        with pd.option_context('display.max_rows', None, 'display.max_columns', None):  # more options can be specified also
            print(Weights)
    else:
        print('Top ' + str(topk) + ' features.')
        print(TopK)
        
        print('\nTop ' + str(topk) + ' negative features.')
        print(Weights.tail(5))
    return None

Discussion 2.3: Interpret Principal Components¶

The highest the absolute weight of a variable in a PCA component means the more impact that this variable has. The interpretation of the positive and negative values shows if the variables are positively or negatively correlated. The impact on the component is on the direction it is going.

For component 1 and based on the absolute value of the weights, the variable with the most impact is MOBI_REGION followed by PLZ8_ANTG1 and PLZ8_ANTG3.

Using the same logic, we can analyse the most important features in all the components created.

One thing that I found interesting is that, for component 3, 8 out of the top 10 most impactuf features (based on absolute value of the weight) are linked to the personality of the person. This is different from component 1 for example that seems to be impacted by variables representing the region of the customer.

My conclusion is that the first component captured variance linked to region of the customers while the second and third components are focusing on variance coming from other variables which, in this case, is the personality and person related variables.

Warning: because of the large size of the dataset, it can take a long time for the algorithm to resolve. The more clusters to fit, the longer the algorithm will take. Discussion 3.1: Apply Clustering to General Population¶

As the number of clusters increased, the average within-cluster distance keeps decreasing. Instead of using score() to calculate it, I used inertia which is the sum of all distances of points to the center of their cluster divided by the number of points.

From the plot showing the change in the average within-cluster distances, I choose 14 clusters. This is because the metric keep decreasing until reaching 14 where it is slightly larger for 15.

In a real life scenario, the number of clusters will also depend on what we want to achieve from every cluster.

Step 3.3: Compare Customer Data to Demographics Data¶

At this point, you have clustered data based on demographics of the general population of Germany, and seen how the customer data for a mail-order sales company maps onto those demographic clusters. In this final substep, you will compare the two cluster distributions to see where the strongest customer base for the company is.

Consider the proportion of persons in each cluster for the general population, and the proportions for the customers. If we think the company's customer base to be universal, then the cluster assignment proportions should be fairly similar between the two. If there are only particular segments of the population that are interested in the company's products, then we should see a mismatch from one to the other. If there is a higher proportion of persons in a cluster for the customer data compared to the general population (e.g. 5% of persons are assigned to a cluster for the general population, but 15% of the customer data is closest to that cluster's centroid) then that suggests the people in that cluster to be a target audience for the company. On the other hand, the proportion of the data in a cluster being larger in the general population than the customer data (e.g. only 2% of customers closest to a population centroid that captures 6% of the data) suggests that group of persons to be outside of the target demographics.

Take a look at the following points in this step:

Discussion 3.3: Compare Customer Data to Demographics Data¶

Popular with the mail-order company - Cluster 13¶

When looking at the distribution of the clusters of customers, more than 30% are in cluster 12. This is selected as the cluster that is popular with the company. By selecting the centroid of the cluster and reversing the PCA transformation, we can go back to the original scaled variables and see their values for the cluster. We can even go back to the unscaled data by reversing the scaling step ((x*std) + mean). However, for simplicity I am just looking at the high/low scaled values.

The 5 highest variables for cluster 13 are MOVEMENT, GREENAVANTGARDE, FINANZ_MINIMALIST, SEMIO_VERT, and KBA05_ANTG1. Based on this and the negative values, we can deduce that the company is popular with wealthy members of green avantgarde who live in area with a high share of 1 - 2 family homes. The customers also have lowest affinity for dreamful in the personality typology.
